      <body>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:lang="grc"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="zoor0261.transcription"
              corresp="#zoor0261.translation">
            <p>+ Εἶς <expan><abbr>θ</abbr><ex>εό</ex><abbr>ς</abbr></expan>, ὁ πάν<lb/>των <expan><abbr>Δεσπ</abbr><ex>ότης.</ex></expan>
               <lb/> Ἐνθάδε <choice>
                  <sic>κῖτε</sic>
                  <corr>κεῖται</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> Βίκτωρ
                    Σιλου<lb/>ανοῦ, ζήσας<lb/> ἐτῶν λεʹ, <choice>
                  <sic>τε<lb/>λευτέσας</sic>
                  <corr>τελευτήσας</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> ἐν μηνὶ <choice>
                  <abbr>Ξαν<lb/>θ,</abbr>
                  <expan>Ξανθικῷ</expan>
               </choice>
               <expan><abbr>ἰνδ</abbr><ex>ικτιῶνος</ex></expan> θʹ, τοῦ<lb/> ἔτ<unclear>ο</unclear>υς
                    υο<unclear>α</unclear>ʹ.<lb/> +</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0261.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0261.transcription">
            <p>One (is) the God, the Lord of all. Here lies Victor, (son) of Silouanos (Silvanus), who
                    lived 35 years, (and) died in the month of Xanthikos, in (the) 9th indiction, in
                    the year 471.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription records the date as the month Xanthikos, during the 9th indiction, in the year 471 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, giving a range of March 22 - April 20, 576 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The tombstone is rectangular, with some chipping. The text is engraved, and preserves some red paint. A cross decorated with linear serifs begins the text, while another cross with serifs is found below the final line. These crosses are incised, and also bear red paint. The author notes that this inscription is the only known attestation of the name Βίκτωρ, Latin “Victor”, at Ghor es-Safi.</p>
         </div>
